    </div>
</div>
                        
                        <p>
    The Cape Hatteras has also been equipped with a webcam that will provide a live feed of what is going on in the gulf to the Nicholas School&rsquo;s website dedicated to providing information about the gulf oil spill.</p>
<p>
    The website &ldquo;Disaster in the Gulf,&rdquo; which was officially launched May 28, features news articles, photos, links to other sites and several blogs, including &ldquo;The Green Grok&rdquo; by Bill Chameides, dean of the Nicholas School.</p>
<p>
    &ldquo;When [the oil spill] happened, we were stunned and as it kept growing and growing, it was clear that we needed a response as one of the world&rsquo;s premier environmental schools,&rdquo; said Tim Lucas, national media relations and marketing specialist at the Nicholas School. &ldquo;We wanted to provide a good source of information for people looking for experts, the latest news and images of the oil spill.&rdquo;</p>
<p>
    Website content is written and organized by Nicholas School staff in addition to their normal academic duties. Headline news on the site comes from various news sources, including The Wall Street Journal, The New York Times and The Washington Post.</p>
<p>
    Lucas added that traffic on the site has been very heavy, with visits from students, alumni, reporters and others trying to stay updated on events in the gulf.</p>
<p>
    &ldquo;[The oil spill] is pretty horrendous and the whole University is reacting,&rdquo; Lucas said. &ldquo;We want to provide the unbiased information and hopefully people will be able to get some use out of it.&rdquo;</p>

